WEBVTT

00:01.335 --> 00:03.295
ELEANOR:
Previously on Black Cake...

00:03.295 --> 00:04.129
BENNY:
Ma is dead.

00:04.129 --> 00:06.507
You didn't even tell me she was sick.

00:07.216 --> 00:08.132
- Read the will, please.

00:08.132 --> 00:09.551
MR. MITCH:
Your mother left you a message.

00:09.551 --> 00:12.930
She wanted you
to listen to all seven recordings.

00:13.972 --> 00:17.809
ELEANOR [on recording]:
Forgive me for keeping so many secrets.

00:17.809 --> 00:22.064
I must confess
that I was not raised in an orphanage.

00:22.689 --> 00:25.192
Eleanor is not my real name.

00:25.192 --> 00:27.152
- Covey! Wait.

00:27.152 --> 00:29.363
I don't have much time left
before I'm off to London.

00:29.363 --> 00:33.450
- Little Man and his brothers
will bleed a man dry to settle a debt.

00:34.284 --> 00:35.202
- Stop!

00:35.702 --> 00:36.870
Don't do this to me.

00:36.870 --> 00:38.413
- The only way
I can get us out of debt

00:38.413 --> 00:39.540
is through this marriage.

00:39.540 --> 00:42.209
ELEANOR:
My father sold his little girl.

00:42.709 --> 00:45.087
COVEY: I want you to know
that when I am another man's property,

00:45.087 --> 00:46.421
you are dead to me.

00:47.005 --> 00:48.549
[choking]

00:48.549 --> 00:49.466
[body thuds]

00:50.008 --> 00:52.010
[people clamoring]

00:54.805 --> 00:56.181
- I didn't kill your brother.

00:56.181 --> 00:57.349
[kicks]
[Lin grunts]

00:57.349 --> 00:58.433
WINSTON:
Then who did?

00:59.893 --> 01:01.228
BUNNY:
Your pa came through.

01:01.228 --> 01:02.229
- They'll kill him.

01:02.229 --> 01:03.897
- You can't worry about him anymore.

01:03.897 --> 01:05.357
There's a ship leaving tonight.

01:05.357 --> 01:08.277
You can get into England
if you travel under your mother's surname.

01:08.277 --> 01:09.695
You'll stay at a boarding house.

01:09.695 --> 01:10.779
You're free.

01:10.779 --> 01:13.699
ELEANOR:
It would take time to get used to London.

01:13.699 --> 01:16.118
- I'm Eleanor,
but you can call me Elly.

01:16.952 --> 01:18.704
ELEANOR:
I didn't realize it then.

01:18.704 --> 01:20.372
But to ensure my safety,

01:21.123 --> 01:23.083
Elly would have to die.

01:29.464 --> 01:31.175
ELEANOR [on recording]:
B and B,

01:31.175 --> 01:35.220
sometimes the stories
we don't tell people about ourselves

01:35.220 --> 01:37.973
matter even more
than the stories we do tell.

01:43.604 --> 01:44.813
All your lives,

01:45.397 --> 01:51.278
I told you a story about a girl
with no family and no past.

01:51.945 --> 01:53.197
But of course,

01:53.822 --> 01:55.616
that's not my story.

01:57.409 --> 02:00.245
[sighs deeply] I'm sorry.

02:01.079 --> 02:03.332
Can we stop, please?

02:03.874 --> 02:04.875
[clicks]

02:05.417 --> 02:08.128
MR. MITCH: Next chapter
of your mother's life was very difficult.

02:08.128 --> 02:11.340
She had so many unresolved emotions,

02:11.340 --> 02:14.927
so much grief about her time in London.

02:14.927 --> 02:16.303
She needed a break.

02:17.304 --> 02:19.306
[insects chirring outside]

02:25.229 --> 02:26.563
- I'm sorry, um,

02:28.148 --> 02:29.316
I've said too much.

02:29.316 --> 02:30.609
- None of this makes sense.

02:31.026 --> 02:33.862
I mean, did Dad know any of this? Jesus.

02:35.656 --> 02:37.991
Ma didn't kill this Elly person, did she?

02:39.535 --> 02:40.536
Or Little Man?

02:40.536 --> 02:42.663
- I know it's very frustrating.

02:42.663 --> 02:45.249
- Frustrating!
MR. MITCH: But you have to keep listening.

02:45.249 --> 02:46.375
- This is insane!

02:47.000 --> 02:48.460
Ma must've lost her mind.

02:50.712 --> 02:53.215
The brain tumor.
That's the only explanation.

02:53.215 --> 02:56.009
- You were here. You would've known.

02:56.009 --> 02:57.094
- Yeah, I didn't know about him.

02:58.136 --> 03:00.097
I didn't know Ma was pouring her heart out

03:00.097 --> 03:03.809
to one of Dad's old lawyer buddies
in a voice recorder app.

03:03.809 --> 03:04.810
I was here,

03:06.562 --> 03:09.606
and yet I still had no idea, Benny.
[sighs]

03:12.943 --> 03:14.736
- By! Stop!

03:14.736 --> 03:17.614
Please, think about what we just learned.

03:17.614 --> 03:20.284
Ma wasn't an orphan. She had a family.

03:20.284 --> 03:23.203
She has a story, our story.

03:23.203 --> 03:25.873
We're Chinese, kind of.

03:25.873 --> 03:27.499
I mean, it's amazing!

03:27.499 --> 03:28.750
- I'm sure it is.

03:29.835 --> 03:31.003
I can't go there.

03:31.670 --> 03:33.964
I can't do this.
- Yes, you can.

03:33.964 --> 03:36.008
We just have to keep listening.

03:36.008 --> 03:37.551
That's what she wanted us to do.

03:37.551 --> 03:39.928
And to be honest,
I won't be able to go to sleep

03:39.928 --> 03:41.305
until I find out what happened in London.

03:41.305 --> 03:45.225
- Look at you, getting off on this
like it's some true-crime podcast.

03:45.225 --> 03:46.393
- Wait, I am not!

03:47.060 --> 03:47.936
But the truth is,

03:47.936 --> 03:49.813
learning that your perfect mother
went through some shit

03:49.813 --> 03:50.772
is kind of comforting

03:50.772 --> 03:52.107
when you spent your entire life

03:52.107 --> 03:54.276
feeling like you could
never live up to her standards.

03:54.276 --> 03:55.277
- Oh, I see.

03:57.029 --> 03:58.447
Ma was messy, hmm?

03:59.031 --> 04:01.533
So are you, and that gives you comfort?
[Benny scoffs]

04:01.533 --> 04:02.868
MR. MITCH:
Okay, now, uh...

04:04.328 --> 04:06.997
Why don't we take a break and regroup?

04:12.085 --> 04:14.671
- Wait. Don't leave me with him.

04:14.671 --> 04:15.964
- Why not?

04:15.964 --> 04:17.841
You two can chat
about what a beautiful mess Ma was.

04:17.841 --> 04:19.468
- Don't be a dick!
BYRON: I'm not.

04:19.468 --> 04:21.136
I have a work thing.
My boss asked me to come in.

04:21.136 --> 04:24.598
- For fuck's sake! Work can wait.
- No, it cannot just wait.

04:25.557 --> 04:27.351
They're about to fill
the new director's position.

04:27.351 --> 04:28.185
[Benny sighs]

04:28.185 --> 04:30.395
- I've been waiting almost a decade
for this promotion,

04:31.355 --> 04:32.314
and I need to be there.

04:33.440 --> 04:35.442
[phone vibrating]
[Benny scoffs]

04:36.860 --> 04:37.861
[sighs]

04:38.654 --> 04:39.905
[phone continues vibrating]

04:42.032 --> 04:42.991
[Benny sighs]

04:47.746 --> 04:48.747
- Tea?

04:48.747 --> 04:50.749
[kettle whistling]

04:56.922 --> 04:58.257
- Can I help you find something?

04:58.257 --> 05:01.301
- Tin milk. Ma kept it up here.

05:01.301 --> 05:04.930
- Near the end, she had trouble
reaching into the cabinets,

05:04.930 --> 05:07.850
so I moved some things around.

05:09.101 --> 05:10.269
Hmm.

05:11.103 --> 05:12.145
[Benny chuckles]

05:13.272 --> 05:17.067
- I cannot imagine
Ma needing anybody's help with anything.

05:17.067 --> 05:18.735
[Mr. Mitch chuckling]

05:18.735 --> 05:19.987
BENNY: Look at this!

05:24.157 --> 05:26.368
Ma gave it to me
when I went off to college

05:26.368 --> 05:29.538
so that I'd always have
a piece of home with me wherever I went.

05:30.414 --> 05:32.791
And I always brought it home
for the holidays

05:32.791 --> 05:34.793
so that we can make
our black cake with it.

05:36.670 --> 05:38.213
It was our tradition.

05:38.213 --> 05:40.215
- How did it end up back here?

05:40.716 --> 05:41.717
- I left it.

05:43.468 --> 05:44.469
Eight years ago.

05:45.596 --> 05:46.889
On Thanksgiving.

05:49.266 --> 05:51.393
And that was the last time
I saw my family.

05:52.811 --> 05:53.812
- There you go.

05:53.812 --> 05:55.063
BENNY:
Oh, thanks.

06:02.070 --> 06:04.656
- I wanted to open my own café,

06:04.656 --> 06:07.451
so I could serve tea just like this.
[chuckles]

06:08.118 --> 06:12.080
I wanted to surprise Byron and Ma

06:12.080 --> 06:16.418
and show them
that I could do something on my own.

06:16.418 --> 06:18.295
- Eleanor was very proud of you.

06:19.338 --> 06:21.548
Oh, she used to go on and on
about your music.

06:21.548 --> 06:26.428
[chuckling] Even got me
to subscribe to your YouTube channel.

06:26.595 --> 06:27.513
[Benny laughs]

06:28.931 --> 06:30.516
- YouTube, man.

06:30.516 --> 06:34.102
God! I haven't posted in so long.

06:34.102 --> 06:35.729
- Oh, you need to pick it back up.

06:37.356 --> 06:40.234
Don't let that voice go to waste.
People need to hear it.

06:41.151 --> 06:42.152
- Thanks.

06:43.570 --> 06:44.613
I'll think about it.

06:51.537 --> 06:54.498
Could you tell me
something else... about Ma?

06:54.498 --> 06:55.707
- Mm.

06:55.707 --> 06:57.125
- Was she

06:59.127 --> 07:00.504
afraid to die?

07:01.421 --> 07:03.715
- Oh, well. [sighs]

07:08.762 --> 07:13.433
I believe she was afraid to, to die
before she finished telling her story,

07:14.476 --> 07:16.645
before you and your brother could hear it.

07:18.397 --> 07:20.357
And you know, Benny,

07:20.357 --> 07:23.151
watching you perform,
even on the computer,

07:23.151 --> 07:27.072
was like getting a peek at... your diary.

07:27.072 --> 07:30.284
I think you inspired her
to leave her own record.

07:30.534 --> 07:32.870
♪ poignant music playing ♪

07:36.081 --> 07:38.292
- You are a great listener.

07:38.292 --> 07:39.835
[Mr. Mitch scoffs]
[Benny laughs]

07:39.835 --> 07:41.336
- I'm a lawyer. [chuckles]

07:43.255 --> 07:44.256
It's my job.

07:46.717 --> 07:48.260
- Is that all this is to you?

07:49.553 --> 07:50.554
A job?

07:50.554 --> 07:53.432
♪

07:59.521 --> 08:00.939
- It's getting late. I better go.

08:00.939 --> 08:03.317
- Are you sure?
I mean, I've-- I really don't mind.

08:03.317 --> 08:04.318
- Look, uh,

08:05.402 --> 08:07.779
whenever Byron's ready to listen again,

08:09.531 --> 08:10.532
give me a call.

08:11.033 --> 08:12.743
Doesn't matter what time.

08:13.243 --> 08:14.411
I'll be here.

08:20.584 --> 08:21.502
[door opens]

08:23.462 --> 08:24.296
[door closes]

08:35.974 --> 08:38.977
♪ somber music playing ♪

09:00.290 --> 09:01.291
[sighs]

09:11.134 --> 09:12.010
[sharp exhale]

09:23.272 --> 09:25.941
♪

09:40.163 --> 09:43.166
♪

09:46.837 --> 09:47.671
[sniffles]

09:57.514 --> 09:59.516
♪

10:07.524 --> 10:08.400
[deep inhale]

10:12.321 --> 10:13.155
[sharp exhale]

10:13.697 --> 10:14.489
[sniffles]

10:17.409 --> 10:20.412
♪

10:28.962 --> 10:31.340
[keypad clacking]

10:33.592 --> 10:34.426
[sniffles]

10:35.886 --> 10:39.181
ELEANOR [on voicemail]:
Benedetta, please come home.

10:39.181 --> 10:40.098
[clicks play again]

10:40.349 --> 10:43.560
ELEANOR:
Benedetta, please come home.

10:44.520 --> 10:45.354
[clicks play again]

10:45.854 --> 10:48.899
[Benny sobbing]
- Benedetta, please come home.

10:56.698 --> 10:59.701
♪

11:09.628 --> 11:10.879
- Dale.

11:10.879 --> 11:14.716
- Byron. I am so sorry for your loss.

11:14.716 --> 11:15.801
- Thank you.

11:15.801 --> 11:17.761
And thank you for the flowers.
I appreciate it.

11:17.761 --> 11:19.012
- Sorry, I, uh--

11:20.138 --> 11:22.641
I got stuck in the lab.

11:22.641 --> 11:24.142
- Please, sit.

11:25.686 --> 11:26.687
- Byron.

11:28.313 --> 11:31.400
DALE: I wanted to take this opportunity
to thank you both

11:31.400 --> 11:33.485
for all of your hard work.

11:33.485 --> 11:34.987
It's been a big year for us,

11:34.987 --> 11:38.740
thanks in no small part
to Byron's recruiting efforts.

11:38.740 --> 11:40.409
You brought a lot of attention
to our field.

11:40.409 --> 11:41.451
- Thank you.

11:41.451 --> 11:45.289
You know, I have
so many ideas for outreach,

11:45.289 --> 11:46.790
including a scholarship program

11:46.790 --> 11:48.792
that will help so many--
MARC: Well, scholarships are great,

11:48.792 --> 11:51.420
but telling kids that
working in ocean sciences

11:51.420 --> 11:52.921
is gonna put 'em on TV is a little--

11:53.463 --> 11:55.340
It's a little bait and switch,
if you ask me.

11:55.340 --> 11:57.050
- It's not bait and switch.

11:57.676 --> 11:59.678
It shows them what is actually possible.

11:59.678 --> 12:03.140
- Listen, I brought you both in here
because you were the only two candidates

12:03.140 --> 12:04.641
we seriously considered.

12:04.641 --> 12:07.728
And although
the public-facing work is valuable,

12:07.728 --> 12:09.855
we can't overlook
the day-to-day in-house work

12:09.855 --> 12:11.815
that often doesn't get the same attention.

12:12.191 --> 12:15.819
In light of your contributions
in that regard, Marc,

12:15.819 --> 12:18.280
next week,
the board will formally announce you

12:18.280 --> 12:20.866
as the new director of the institute.

12:21.700 --> 12:22.701
MARC:
Oh!

12:23.285 --> 12:25.078
Wow. It's--

12:25.829 --> 12:26.997
It's an honor. Thank you.

12:27.789 --> 12:30.542
- Byron, it was a tough decision,

12:31.585 --> 12:33.045
but it was unanimous.

12:33.795 --> 12:36.757
You will be reporting to Marc
from this day forward.

12:38.717 --> 12:39.718
- Understood.

12:42.387 --> 12:43.764
Congratulations, Marc.

12:44.932 --> 12:45.933
You earned it.

12:47.518 --> 12:48.519
- Thanks, Byron.

12:54.191 --> 12:55.192
[door closes]

12:57.069 --> 13:00.072
♪ melancholic music playing ♪

13:14.253 --> 13:15.254
- Hey.

13:17.005 --> 13:18.382
- Oh, hey.

13:20.050 --> 13:21.343
I called Mr. Mitch.

13:22.261 --> 13:23.220
He's on his way.

13:23.804 --> 13:24.805
I wanna get this over with.

13:26.849 --> 13:27.850
- Okay.

13:29.685 --> 13:30.894
How was your work thing?

13:32.563 --> 13:35.023
Should I start calling you boss?

13:38.026 --> 13:39.528
- They haven't made a decision yet.

13:41.029 --> 13:42.030
I need a drink.

13:46.660 --> 13:50.414
- Thank you for taking care
of the funeral arrangements for Ma.

13:53.625 --> 13:55.210
And for Dad.

13:55.210 --> 13:56.420
BYRON:
It's all good.

13:57.254 --> 13:58.088
Really.

13:59.131 --> 14:00.716
- I wanna help, By.

14:01.550 --> 14:02.593
What can I do?

14:02.593 --> 14:03.594
- You're here.

14:05.679 --> 14:06.847
That's enough.

14:07.890 --> 14:09.683
Here's to the past.

14:10.392 --> 14:12.019
May it not blow up our present.

14:12.603 --> 14:13.437
[Benny sighs]

14:14.438 --> 14:15.230
[glasses clink]

14:17.274 --> 14:18.358
[Byron chuckles]

14:34.249 --> 14:35.083
[clicks]

14:35.083 --> 14:39.379
ELEANOR [on recording]:
B and B, I'm sorry I had to take a break.

14:40.464 --> 14:42.299
I know this must be a shock,

14:42.299 --> 14:47.596
but I'm telling you this now
because this is your story too.

14:48.555 --> 14:50.516
And hopefully, after hearing it,

14:51.141 --> 14:54.269
you'll share your stories with each other

14:54.269 --> 14:56.146
before it's too late.

14:57.940 --> 14:59.942
As with many stories,

15:01.193 --> 15:04.029
this one revolves around luck.

15:06.114 --> 15:08.659
I was lucky to be settling into London.

15:09.535 --> 15:12.955
But I was so far
from everyone I cared about,

15:13.789 --> 15:15.749
I'm not sure I would ever see them again.

15:15.832 --> 15:17.668
[rain falling, thunder claps]

15:17.793 --> 15:21.922
ELEANOR:
Along with the forged documents
using my mum's maiden name,

15:23.006 --> 15:27.302
Pearl sent a note,
warning me to stay away from crowds

15:27.302 --> 15:29.304
or anywhere I might be recognized.

15:31.098 --> 15:34.601
I could no longer be Covey Lyncook,

15:34.601 --> 15:37.771
the girl with the chiney father
and the runaway mother.

15:38.647 --> 15:41.191
I was Coventina Brown,

15:42.234 --> 15:43.485
a blank slate.

15:44.444 --> 15:49.116
And I would protect my new identity
at any cost.

15:56.331 --> 15:57.875
[rain falling]

15:59.751 --> 16:01.003
- Ready to go?

16:01.003 --> 16:03.380
You don't want to be late
on your first day.

16:03.380 --> 16:04.464
- Almost.

16:09.803 --> 16:12.764
- Coventina, your sneakers will fall apart
in this rain!

16:12.764 --> 16:14.391
You better put your wellies on.

16:14.391 --> 16:15.642
- These are the only shoes I have.

16:15.642 --> 16:18.979
- You're from the mountains.
How could you have left your boots behind?

16:18.979 --> 16:22.191
- Oh, I guess
I must've packed in a dash, didn't I?

16:22.858 --> 16:24.902
Don't worry. I'll manage.

16:25.736 --> 16:27.905
- Not without proper rain gear.

16:28.822 --> 16:30.282
But we'll deal with that later.

16:31.909 --> 16:33.118
Let's go.

16:33.118 --> 16:35.454
♪

16:35.454 --> 16:37.206
I'll walk you to the bus stop.

16:37.206 --> 16:41.627
From there, you'll catch
any Route 2 bus north. 2, 2A, 2B.

16:41.627 --> 16:43.837
Switch at Victoria Station.

16:43.837 --> 16:48.008
From there, you'll catch a Route 24 bus
headed north towards Hampstead.

16:48.008 --> 16:51.428
Your stop is Chalk Farm Road
near Primrose Hill.

16:51.428 --> 16:53.555
Ooh, and there's
a great sweet shop near there.

16:59.686 --> 17:00.812
This isn't your bus.

17:00.812 --> 17:03.649
You're looking
for a Route 2 bus, remember?

17:03.649 --> 17:05.067
You look nervous.

17:05.067 --> 17:06.818
Don't be nervous. You'll do great.

17:13.909 --> 17:15.744
[knocking at door]

17:20.999 --> 17:23.669
- Good day, ma'am. I'm Coventina Brown,

17:23.669 --> 17:25.838
your new nanny from the boarding house.

17:26.755 --> 17:29.716
I know that I'm two minutes late,
and I apologize.

17:29.716 --> 17:30.926
It won't happen again.

17:34.054 --> 17:35.722
- Fresh off the boat, are you?

17:36.598 --> 17:39.142
They usually send us girls
who've been here a bit longer,

17:39.768 --> 17:41.103
but we'll see how things go.

17:43.772 --> 17:47.067
Well, don't just stand there.
Come inside and remove those wet garments.

17:51.947 --> 17:54.950
♪

17:56.618 --> 17:59.413
Your job is to manage
the children's affairs

17:59.413 --> 18:01.248
and make sure they look presentable.

18:02.583 --> 18:04.918
You are to be presentable as well.

18:09.965 --> 18:12.759
That's Jing. She's been with us for years.

18:13.844 --> 18:17.389
Mr. Quintrell and I
are very... forward thinkers.

18:27.357 --> 18:28.817
[child hooting]
[Mrs. Quintrell clapping]

18:30.110 --> 18:33.488
- Theo, Pepper,
this is Ms. Coventina Brown.

18:34.114 --> 18:35.574
She is here to take care of you

18:36.325 --> 18:37.242
but not your toys.

18:37.242 --> 18:39.244
You will put them away yourselves,
won't you?

18:39.244 --> 18:40.245
CHILDREN:
Yes, Mummy.

18:40.245 --> 18:42.206
- Good. Now come greet her.

18:43.040 --> 18:44.666
- Pleased to meet you.

18:44.666 --> 18:46.418
- Please to meet you too, Theo.

18:56.094 --> 18:57.095
Thank you.

18:58.013 --> 19:00.474
ELEANOR:
I was learning to play my new part.

19:00.474 --> 19:03.644
And I was lucky
to find comfort in a few places.

19:04.770 --> 19:07.481
Although
every time I thought I could relax,

19:07.981 --> 19:11.735
a new threat would turn up
where I least expected.

19:11.777 --> 19:13.070
[indistinct chatter]

19:14.112 --> 19:17.157
- New girl, come to the docks with us.

19:17.866 --> 19:21.703
- It's Coventina.
And what's at the docks?

19:22.204 --> 19:24.998
- A boat from home
arrives every Friday night, silly.

19:24.998 --> 19:27.501
Same boat you come on a few weeks ago.

19:27.501 --> 19:29.336
- A new boat arrives every week?

19:29.336 --> 19:32.422
- Yeah, and we're the welcome party!
- Mm-hmm.

19:32.422 --> 19:33.423
[girls laughing]

19:34.007 --> 19:35.008
- How lovely.

19:35.759 --> 19:38.387
Are you expecting family, friends?

19:38.387 --> 19:40.764
- No. That's the fun of it.

19:41.306 --> 19:43.058
There is no passengers list.

19:43.058 --> 19:45.102
You never know who's going to be there.

19:45.686 --> 19:46.937
Could be your soulmate.

19:46.937 --> 19:49.314
- Or your worst enemy.
- Mm-hmm.

19:49.314 --> 19:50.649
[girls laughing]

19:51.733 --> 19:53.068
EDWINA:
Go clean up.

19:53.068 --> 19:56.154
Put on something
with a little... personality.

19:56.905 --> 19:59.408
You look like a drowned rat. [chuckles]

19:59.408 --> 20:00.909
- Thank you for inviting me,

20:00.909 --> 20:03.787
but... [exhales] I've had a long day.

20:04.288 --> 20:05.289
Maybe next time.

20:05.747 --> 20:06.582
[Lorna scoffs]

20:08.000 --> 20:09.793
- I told you she weren't gonna come.
- Mm.

20:23.473 --> 20:25.851
ELEANOR:
I wanted to see the big city.

20:26.685 --> 20:29.730
I wanted to gossip about boys and clothes.

20:31.523 --> 20:33.150
But it was too dangerous.

20:34.484 --> 20:38.739
The thought of Little Man's brothers
showing up on one of those boats

20:38.739 --> 20:40.532
was too much for me to bear.

20:41.617 --> 20:42.743
Why push my luck?

20:44.244 --> 20:45.078
[sighs]

20:46.038 --> 20:49.041
♪

20:54.546 --> 20:55.547
[knocker clangs]

20:58.842 --> 21:00.844
[women chatting indistinctly]

21:03.263 --> 21:04.806
ELEANOR:
I kept my head down

21:05.724 --> 21:07.684
and tried to do what I was told.

21:14.441 --> 21:17.778
I tried to focus on each day as it came

21:18.195 --> 21:20.572
and not let myself dwell on the past.

21:20.572 --> 21:24.284
♪ Easy Come Easy Go
by The Pioneers playing ♪

21:28.580 --> 21:32.501
- ♪ Bum-bum, bum-ba-dum-da-dum,
bum-bum ♪

21:32.584 --> 21:35.504
[people chattering]

21:40.092 --> 21:42.219
ELEANOR:
But as the months wore on,

21:43.136 --> 21:46.181
the loneliness became unbearable.

21:57.860 --> 21:59.862
♪ melancholic music playing ♪

22:11.832 --> 22:15.752
It was getting harder and harder
to remain invisible.

22:16.837 --> 22:18.505
I needed to be seen,

22:19.256 --> 22:20.883
and I thought maybe,

22:22.009 --> 22:23.510
just maybe,

22:24.261 --> 22:25.387
there was a way.

22:27.097 --> 22:29.516
If I wanted to be seen,

22:30.184 --> 22:32.561
to be held, to be me,

22:33.270 --> 22:34.688
I could skip my stop

22:35.439 --> 22:37.232
and ride up to the university

22:37.232 --> 22:39.526
where I thought Gibbs might be studying.

22:41.111 --> 22:42.237
But if I saw him,

22:43.488 --> 22:44.698
what would I say?

22:45.991 --> 22:48.243
It was too dangerous.

22:48.994 --> 22:50.037
And yet,

22:50.621 --> 22:52.664
I had to do something.

22:55.334 --> 22:58.128
And so I remembered Bunny's advice,

22:58.629 --> 23:03.592
and I let my mind drift back
to the tastes and flavors of home.

23:22.069 --> 23:23.070
- What this?

23:24.029 --> 23:25.948
You're supposed to make
fish and chips today.

23:25.948 --> 23:28.242
- I thought I'd make something special.

23:28.242 --> 23:29.576
A recipe from home.

23:37.125 --> 23:37.960
[slurps]

23:40.254 --> 23:41.547
- This is Chinese soup.

23:42.798 --> 23:44.341
How did you learn to make it?

23:44.341 --> 23:47.302
- My grandmother had a Chinese neighbor.

23:48.846 --> 23:50.264
I should finish cooking.

23:50.889 --> 23:53.433
Children will turn if they don't eat soon.

23:56.019 --> 24:00.065
ELEANOR: I was determined
to keep my memories of home alive.

24:00.774 --> 24:04.570
And although it was a risk,
it was one I was willing to take.

24:05.237 --> 24:08.240
♪

24:08.240 --> 24:10.242
[rain falling]

24:14.663 --> 24:15.664
- What is it?

24:16.331 --> 24:17.332
- Fish soup.

24:17.833 --> 24:19.168
I know it's not fish and chips,

24:19.168 --> 24:22.838
but I think you're going to love
how it just melts in your mouth.

24:24.298 --> 24:27.509
- Blegh! Yuck! Gross!

24:27.509 --> 24:30.470
ELEANOR:
But the truth was finally sinking in:

24:30.470 --> 24:32.639
I could never go back again.

24:32.639 --> 24:34.391
- I wanted fish and chips, you know?

24:39.938 --> 24:40.898
[door opening]

24:43.400 --> 24:45.652
[Covey sniffling]

24:56.371 --> 24:58.415
[Covey continues sniffling]

25:00.667 --> 25:01.627
- Coventina.

25:02.503 --> 25:03.587
Are you okay?

25:04.296 --> 25:05.297
- [crying] I'm fine.

25:06.340 --> 25:08.133
Just pretend I'm not here, all right?

25:08.133 --> 25:10.010
- I will do no such thing.

25:10.010 --> 25:11.803
- Please, I've had a bad day, is all.

25:11.803 --> 25:13.555
I really don't want to talk about it.

25:15.599 --> 25:17.184
- Would it make you feel better

25:17.184 --> 25:19.811
if I told you
I had a pretty dreadful day myself?

25:23.732 --> 25:24.733
- It might.

25:26.527 --> 25:27.444
- Well...

25:28.529 --> 25:30.030
I hate to say it,

25:30.030 --> 25:33.617
but this nursing program
isn't what I had hoped.

25:33.617 --> 25:36.745
I'm spending my days
cleaning bedpans and commodes

25:36.745 --> 25:38.413
instead of treating patients.

25:38.413 --> 25:43.001
And I'm having a hard time seeing myself
doing that for the rest of my life.

25:43.502 --> 25:44.878
- That's dreadful, Elly.

25:46.171 --> 25:47.548
You work so hard.

25:48.298 --> 25:51.260
If your laundry pile didn't grow,
I would've thought you never came home.

25:55.722 --> 26:00.394
I know how lonely it can be
when you first arrive from the islands.

26:03.188 --> 26:05.065
- I miss the colors of the fruit trees,

26:05.774 --> 26:06.942
the people,

26:09.528 --> 26:10.529
and the sea.

26:12.823 --> 26:15.284
I wouldn't go a day
without swimming in it back home.

26:16.368 --> 26:19.705
- Your grandmother would drive you
down the mountain to the beach every day?

26:20.873 --> 26:23.375
- Yes. She knew how much it meant to me,

26:24.376 --> 26:26.086
especially after my mum passed.

26:27.296 --> 26:28.714
- She sounds wonderful.

26:35.137 --> 26:36.471
When I'm homesick,

26:41.810 --> 26:43.187
I turn to these.

26:47.983 --> 26:48.984
[shells rattling]

26:49.693 --> 26:51.236
- Cockleshells.

26:51.236 --> 26:52.529
- From home.

26:53.155 --> 26:54.698
The orphanage where I grew up.

26:54.698 --> 26:56.158
- The orphanage?

26:56.158 --> 26:58.327
- My parents died when I was quite young.

26:59.453 --> 27:02.831
- Elly... I'm so sorry. I didn't know.

27:02.831 --> 27:04.875
- It's not something I like to share.

27:05.501 --> 27:07.544
People hear you're an orphan,
they pity you.

27:07.544 --> 27:09.171
They make judgments.

27:09.171 --> 27:11.757
Being the new girl is hard enough
without all of that.

27:15.302 --> 27:18.639
It took me months
to settle into my life at the orphanage,

27:19.264 --> 27:21.934
and it will take you time
to settle in here.

27:21.934 --> 27:23.644
You have to find ways to cope.

27:24.269 --> 27:26.480
- How did you... cope?

27:26.480 --> 27:28.273
- By distracting myself.

27:29.399 --> 27:31.902
I would dig in the garden for hours.

27:32.611 --> 27:34.488
It's where I found these shells.

27:34.488 --> 27:35.989
It was the most curious thing,

27:35.989 --> 27:38.575
because the orphanage
was nowhere near the sea,

27:39.326 --> 27:40.536
and yet there they were.

27:40.536 --> 27:42.037
- How you think they got there?

27:42.037 --> 27:43.330
- Time.

27:43.330 --> 27:47.292
Millions of years ago,
the island was underwater,

27:47.292 --> 27:49.586
and as the earth erupted and shifted,

27:49.586 --> 27:52.256
Jamaica rose up with the shells.

27:52.422 --> 27:53.257
[slight chuckle]

27:53.757 --> 27:56.510
- I fell in love with geology
after reading about that,

27:56.510 --> 28:00.681
and the idea that everything
is connected to everything else

28:01.306 --> 28:03.141
if you only go back far enough.

28:05.060 --> 28:08.522
- You lit up just now,
speaking about geology.

28:08.522 --> 28:11.567
If nursing doesn't excite you,
why not study that?

28:12.985 --> 28:14.945
- They were recruiting
girls from the islands

28:14.945 --> 28:16.446
into this nursing program.

28:17.447 --> 28:18.866
It was my way out.

28:20.033 --> 28:21.743
And I didn't know until recently

28:21.743 --> 28:25.247
that there's a university in Edinburgh
that specializes in geology,

28:25.247 --> 28:26.957
but it's too late now.

28:28.166 --> 28:30.502
- It's never too late
to pursue your dreams.

28:31.795 --> 28:32.796
- So you say.

28:33.463 --> 28:35.215
But is nannying yours?

28:36.717 --> 28:37.634
- No.

28:39.303 --> 28:40.304
Swimming was.

28:41.263 --> 28:42.264
Is.

28:42.264 --> 28:43.265
I think.

28:44.892 --> 28:46.268
I don't know anymore.

28:46.810 --> 28:47.895
- Well then,

28:48.645 --> 28:49.646
look at us.

28:50.689 --> 28:51.982
Aren't we pathetic?

28:51.982 --> 28:53.442
[both laugh]

28:54.985 --> 28:56.987
♪ poignant music playing ♪

29:08.248 --> 29:09.625
- My mum left this to me.

29:10.292 --> 29:13.420
The stone reminds me of the sea so much,

29:13.420 --> 29:14.963
it hurts to even look at it.

29:14.963 --> 29:16.298
- It's beautiful.

29:17.257 --> 29:18.759
And rare.

29:18.759 --> 29:20.219
Don't hide it away.

29:20.928 --> 29:23.388
If it comforts you, wear it.

29:24.056 --> 29:25.390
Here, let me.

29:35.692 --> 29:39.112
See? Maybe remembering
doesn't have to hurt.

29:39.112 --> 29:42.115
♪

29:50.290 --> 29:52.376
[thunder rumbling]

29:53.794 --> 29:56.797
♪ light music playing ♪

30:08.559 --> 30:11.562
♪

30:25.367 --> 30:27.244
ELEANOR:
Elly gave me hope.

30:28.036 --> 30:30.289
She gave me permission to be me,

30:32.165 --> 30:35.294
permission to find ways
to feel connected to home

30:36.712 --> 30:38.714
without jeopardizing my safety.

30:38.714 --> 30:40.090
♪ Ride Away by The Revlons playing ♪

30:40.090 --> 30:42.551
- ♪ Oh, no, no, ride away ♪

30:43.510 --> 30:45.971
♪ Oh-oh-oh-oh, oh ♪

30:45.971 --> 30:47.347
♪ Ride away ♪

30:48.348 --> 30:50.392
♪ Oh... ♪

30:51.643 --> 30:55.022
- Congratulations. You did it.
[chuckles]

30:56.481 --> 30:58.275
- I am officially Nurse Elly.

30:58.942 --> 31:01.778
Why do I feel like
I'm celebrating the death of a dream?

31:01.778 --> 31:02.779
- Stop it.

31:02.779 --> 31:05.866
We're celebrating the fact
that you're done living in a library,

31:05.866 --> 31:07.784
and you finally have time
for a little fun.

31:07.784 --> 31:09.828
- I can certainly drink to that.

31:09.828 --> 31:13.582
- Ooh, Coventina!
I didn't know you could bake.

31:13.582 --> 31:17.169
- Careful, she put so much rum in there,
you'll surely get drunk off the fumes.

31:17.169 --> 31:18.670
- Ooh!
[Elly and Lorna laugh]

31:18.670 --> 31:19.796
- Come, let's dance.

31:21.590 --> 31:22.591
EDWINA:
Coventina!

31:25.344 --> 31:27.012
Here's an early Christmas gift.

31:27.012 --> 31:28.514
This is Delroy.

31:28.514 --> 31:29.765
He's from Moorton,

31:29.765 --> 31:31.600
right by where you're from
in the mountains.

31:31.600 --> 31:33.936
- We probably know
some of the same people back home.

31:33.936 --> 31:36.021
- It's a small world, isn't it?

31:36.563 --> 31:37.648
When did you get into town?

31:37.648 --> 31:39.107
- Just last week.

31:39.107 --> 31:41.485
But I have a job
lined up already in the new year.

31:41.485 --> 31:43.987
- So he can afford
to take a girl out on a proper date.

31:44.863 --> 31:47.616
DELROY: Coventina,
which school did you go to in Maryville?

31:47.616 --> 31:49.368
My aunt's a teacher over at Stanton.

31:50.661 --> 31:53.372
- Oh, that's where I went, Stanton.

31:54.957 --> 31:56.750
- [chuckles]
I didn't realize it was co-ed.

31:57.334 --> 31:59.878
- Just since the last few years, yes.

31:59.878 --> 32:02.756
- Oh, hm. Well, you must know my aunt.

32:02.756 --> 32:04.424
She goes by Mrs. B at the school.

32:05.050 --> 32:07.761
- Sure. Of course. She was wonderful.

32:07.761 --> 32:09.972
[Delroy laughs]

32:09.972 --> 32:11.807
- I was always terrified of her.

32:11.807 --> 32:13.433
She was so strict with us.

32:13.433 --> 32:15.894
Mm. Maybe she was nice around the girls.

32:17.354 --> 32:18.146
[chuckles]

32:18.522 --> 32:21.024
- You know what? I need a drink.

32:21.024 --> 32:22.067
Can I get you one?

32:22.526 --> 32:24.236
- Sure. Whatever you're having.

32:29.074 --> 32:30.284
- Why you lying?

32:31.743 --> 32:34.037
- Uh-- Um...

32:34.037 --> 32:35.581
- And I know you don't drink.

32:35.581 --> 32:38.667
[chuckles] You're so nervous around boys.

32:38.667 --> 32:40.586
It's kinda cute, actually.

32:41.712 --> 32:44.715
- You're right.
I just never know what to say.

32:44.715 --> 32:46.341
- Doesn't matter what you say.

32:46.341 --> 32:48.427
They just wanna hear themselves talk.

32:48.427 --> 32:50.512
But Delroy is sweet,

32:50.512 --> 32:53.765
and he might make you less homesick,
if you catch my drift.

32:54.641 --> 32:57.936
- I don't know.
He's not the kinda guy I usually go for.

32:58.854 --> 33:01.899
- Well, if you don't like him,
maybe you'll like one of his friends.

33:01.899 --> 33:03.901
He said he knows a few boys
coming in next week,

33:03.901 --> 33:05.402
and they're from the same town as him.

33:09.531 --> 33:10.532
What is it?

33:11.408 --> 33:13.535
What aren't you telling us, Coventina?

33:13.535 --> 33:16.413
- Oh, stop trying to pawn
that boy off on her, Edwina!

33:16.413 --> 33:17.998
You're a bad influence on us all.

33:21.210 --> 33:25.130
Edwina is a fast girl.
Don't let her pressure you.

33:25.130 --> 33:26.548
Come on, let's dance.

33:27.466 --> 33:30.469
♪ Have a Good Time
by The Skatalites playing ♪

33:42.606 --> 33:46.860
- ♪ Goodbye, I hate to see you go... ♪

33:47.903 --> 33:50.948
ELEANOR: My luck
was not going to hold out much longer.

33:51.782 --> 33:55.118
I had to take fate into my own hands.

33:55.118 --> 33:56.954
[heavy breaths]

34:01.875 --> 34:02.876
[door opens]

34:13.804 --> 34:14.805
[Elly chuckles]

34:18.976 --> 34:19.810
- Oh!

34:20.435 --> 34:21.478
You're awake?

34:21.478 --> 34:22.688
- I couldn't sleep.

34:22.688 --> 34:24.731
I've been thinking and--

34:29.820 --> 34:32.072
Before you're stuck in a job you hate,

34:33.699 --> 34:35.242
what if you rolled the dice

34:35.242 --> 34:38.495
and studied geology
at that university in Edinburgh?

34:38.495 --> 34:40.622
- [chuckling] Oh, you can't be serious.

34:40.622 --> 34:42.791
I start nursing after Christmas!

34:42.791 --> 34:44.918
- You need to follow your passion.

34:44.918 --> 34:47.588
And-- And you won't be alone.
I'll go with you.

34:47.588 --> 34:49.923
- Why would you want to go to Scotland?

34:49.923 --> 34:52.885
You'd have to find a new job,
a new place to live.

34:52.885 --> 34:55.470
- We've saved enough money
to get by for a while.

34:57.598 --> 35:01.393
You owe it to that little girl
who spent hours digging in a garden.

35:03.020 --> 35:04.646
The girl who found those cockleshells.

35:08.233 --> 35:10.903
If she had the opportunity
to pursue her dreams,

35:12.863 --> 35:14.823
what would she do, Elly?

35:14.823 --> 35:17.826
♪

35:19.411 --> 35:21.705
[train horn blaring]

35:30.672 --> 35:32.216
[indistinct chatter]

35:33.509 --> 35:34.801
- Almost there. [chuckles]

35:35.469 --> 35:37.763
We'll ring in the new year
with our new lives.

35:37.763 --> 35:38.597
[both giggle]

35:44.186 --> 35:45.187
Coventina,

35:46.855 --> 35:49.483
when I told you about my past,

35:49.483 --> 35:51.443
I was afraid that you might judge me,

35:52.653 --> 35:53.904
but you listened.

35:55.447 --> 35:58.575
Thank you for making me feel
safe enough to share

35:59.409 --> 36:01.370
and for encouraging me to leave.

36:02.996 --> 36:04.414
- I should be thanking you.

36:05.749 --> 36:07.793
When you opened up to me
about your childhood,

36:08.669 --> 36:10.254
I was at my lowest.

36:12.005 --> 36:17.427
It was my 18th birthday,
and... I'd never felt so alone.

36:17.427 --> 36:20.430
- Coventina! If I'd known,
we would've celebrated proper!

36:21.181 --> 36:24.059
- Don't be sorry.
You gave me the best gift.

36:24.059 --> 36:25.769
You gave me permission to be me.

36:26.353 --> 36:28.897
- I wouldn't want you to be anything else.

36:32.776 --> 36:33.610
- Elly...

36:35.529 --> 36:36.989
I'm not from the mountains.

36:37.948 --> 36:41.118
I grew up by the sea in Portland Parish.

36:42.661 --> 36:44.913
- That explains the lack of rain gear.

36:47.040 --> 36:48.083
And the swimming.

36:49.168 --> 36:53.922
- I swam so that one day
I could compete around the world.

36:55.924 --> 36:56.758
And now--

36:58.051 --> 37:01.763
Well, it's-- it's hard to explain.

37:05.058 --> 37:06.059
- It's okay.

37:06.602 --> 37:10.189
Whatever it is,
you don't need to tell me today.

37:10.898 --> 37:11.899
Or ever.

37:12.733 --> 37:14.735
But... when you're ready,

37:16.153 --> 37:17.279
I'll be here.

37:17.279 --> 37:19.406
WAITER:
Tea. Here we are, dear.

37:19.406 --> 37:20.574
- Thank you.

37:30.542 --> 37:33.712
- I wish they served tea with tin milk
like they do back home.

37:37.841 --> 37:40.344
ELLY:
Edwina and the girls will never notice.

37:40.344 --> 37:42.012
[both laughing]

37:57.778 --> 37:58.779
To Scotland.

37:58.779 --> 38:00.989
[train horn blaring]

38:00.989 --> 38:02.241
[wheels screeching]

38:02.241 --> 38:04.243
[thudding in slow-motion]

38:04.243 --> 38:07.037
♪ dramatic music playing ♪

38:10.207 --> 38:13.210
[people screaming]

38:25.806 --> 38:28.809
♪ tense music playing ♪

38:31.562 --> 38:34.523
[people screaming, groaning]

38:51.039 --> 38:51.874
[winces]

38:56.336 --> 38:58.005
[indistinct shouting]

39:03.427 --> 39:05.345
ELEANOR:
As I waited to die,

39:05.345 --> 39:09.266
I wondered what stories
Pa had been telling himself

39:09.266 --> 39:10.767
to get through the day

39:10.767 --> 39:12.561
since I died the first time,

39:13.478 --> 39:16.398
and what stories would he have
to tell everyone else

39:17.024 --> 39:20.027
when news of the train crash
reached the island,

39:20.944 --> 39:24.114
when my death was no longer speculation.

39:24.114 --> 39:27.075
- We are a community in mourning,

39:28.285 --> 39:34.124
to have lost not one
but two of our very own this past year.

39:34.124 --> 39:37.878
While we may have
many unanswered questions,

39:37.878 --> 39:40.339
we must take comfort

39:40.339 --> 39:45.177
that God will see to it
that Sister Covey Lyncook

39:45.177 --> 39:50.057
and Brother Clarence Henry
did not die in vain.

39:50.057 --> 39:53.352
We must honor their legacies,

39:53.352 --> 39:57.064
and that is how we can honor God.

39:57.064 --> 39:58.565
[congregation quietly murmurs]

39:58.565 --> 39:59.733
PASTOR DENNIS:
Let us pray.

40:00.526 --> 40:03.529
♪ mournful choral music playing ♪

40:11.703 --> 40:15.415
- Losing your best friend
can feel like losing a limb.

40:18.377 --> 40:20.629
That's how I felt when Matilda left.

40:23.549 --> 40:27.970
But at least we know
where Covey is now, Bunny.

40:30.848 --> 40:32.724
You don't have to wonder anymore.

40:36.311 --> 40:38.939
- I'm not wondering anything, Pearl.

40:41.984 --> 40:42.943
It's over.

40:44.653 --> 40:47.656
[indistinct chatter]

40:50.784 --> 40:52.661
- You've been
following me around for months.

40:52.661 --> 40:55.497
My daughter, your prime suspect, is dead.

40:55.497 --> 40:56.498
Case closed.

40:57.082 --> 41:00.085
- That's where you're wrong.
This case is still open.

41:00.085 --> 41:01.670
She was never the only suspect.

41:02.129 --> 41:03.130
She couldn't have acted alone,

41:03.130 --> 41:06.550
and the fact that she turned up overseas
using her mother's maiden name

41:06.550 --> 41:09.887
makes it pretty clear to me
that someone helped her escape.

41:14.975 --> 41:18.103
But don't worry, Lyncook.
You're not the only one we're looking at.

41:29.740 --> 41:30.741
- You okay?

41:31.366 --> 41:32.367
- I'm fine.

41:32.910 --> 41:35.537
- That is what you've been saying
since we get the news about Covey.

41:36.788 --> 41:38.665
Your behavior says otherwise.

41:39.291 --> 41:43.045
- I'm tired of all the questions
and the pitiful looks and the gossip.

41:43.045 --> 41:45.005
I said I'm fine, and I meant it!

41:46.131 --> 41:47.132
- Leonard.

41:48.425 --> 41:50.928
You've not come by my ways
since the wedding.

41:50.928 --> 41:53.430
- I'm sorry, Lin,
for your loss, for everything,

41:53.430 --> 41:54.681
but I need to go after Bunny.

41:54.681 --> 41:56.266
She's not the same without Covey.

41:58.185 --> 42:00.145
- Yeah, I understand.

42:00.854 --> 42:02.773
I could've used a friend myself
these past few months.

42:02.773 --> 42:05.734
- I wanted to reach out,
but people are so desperate for gossip.

42:06.318 --> 42:08.320
Quick to accuse anyone
who was close to Covey.

42:08.320 --> 42:09.363
- Yeah, I'm well aware.

42:11.156 --> 42:11.990
- And are you aware

42:11.990 --> 42:14.910
that people have been saying
Bunny was too close to Covey?

42:16.161 --> 42:18.705
I don't need to tell you
how dangerous that is.

42:18.705 --> 42:20.457
- I'm sorry, Leonard--
- You should be.

42:20.457 --> 42:24.086
You invited danger into all of our lives
when you married Covey off,

42:24.086 --> 42:26.296
but I won't let you
ruin Bunny's life too.

42:32.845 --> 42:35.514
[Bunny panting]

42:39.142 --> 42:41.144
[waves crashing]
[birds squawking]

42:50.112 --> 42:53.699
♪ somber music playing ♪

42:55.993 --> 42:57.327
[softly weeping]

43:03.125 --> 43:04.418
- Bunny, what is it?

43:10.048 --> 43:11.800
You can't keep it all inside.

43:15.137 --> 43:17.139
- I haven't been able
to swim since she left.

43:17.139 --> 43:19.474
I need to swim in the harbor race, Daddy.

43:19.474 --> 43:21.059
It was our dream. I--

43:21.977 --> 43:23.353
[voice breaking]
I can't give up on it.

43:29.151 --> 43:30.152
- Okay.

43:30.861 --> 43:31.778
Okay.

43:33.864 --> 43:35.240
How can I help you?

43:35.782 --> 43:36.700
- I don't know.

43:38.160 --> 43:40.704
Covey pushed me. She made me better. I--

43:42.873 --> 43:43.874
I need her.

43:52.591 --> 43:54.343
- Do you remember Jimmy Paterson?

43:54.760 --> 43:57.554
He's a coach now and a fine young man.

43:59.306 --> 44:01.183
He ask about you all the time.

44:02.935 --> 44:04.728
I think he'd be good for you.

44:04.728 --> 44:07.147
- Are you setting me up with a coach
or on a date?

44:07.147 --> 44:10.567
- I won't be around forever
to protect you.

44:12.236 --> 44:13.612
Please think about it.

44:20.202 --> 44:25.749
ELEANOR: My marriage to Little Man
changed the course of all our lives.

44:27.376 --> 44:31.672
And although I'd always hoped
that by going along with his plan

44:31.672 --> 44:33.507
I was protecting Pa,

44:34.216 --> 44:36.385
I wonder whether it was all for nothing,

44:36.385 --> 44:39.388
and whether his choices
ever caught up to him.

44:39.388 --> 44:43.809
WINSTON/PERCIVAL [singing]:
♪ You done stole my belongings
and give to your China man ♪

44:47.020 --> 44:48.021
[speaking Patois]

44:51.984 --> 44:53.694
- You dipping your cock
at the fights again?

44:54.111 --> 44:55.612
- Business has been slow.
[cash register dings]

44:55.612 --> 44:57.531
- Ah. You thought
you were smart sending her off

44:57.531 --> 44:59.241
with her runaway mother maiden name.

44:59.241 --> 45:00.075
[Percival chuckes]

45:00.075 --> 45:02.452
- But now your Black head,
chiney daughter dead.

45:02.452 --> 45:05.747
- And we're not going to let you
run our brother's shop into the ground,

45:06.707 --> 45:10.210
just like how you run
all the women out your life. [laughs]

45:11.461 --> 45:12.462
So get out.

45:12.462 --> 45:13.380
- No.

45:14.882 --> 45:16.341
This is my family's shop.

45:16.341 --> 45:17.676
- Not anymore.

45:19.011 --> 45:22.014
♪ ominous music playing ♪

45:22.806 --> 45:24.016
[cash register drawer shuts]

45:24.975 --> 45:25.851
[Lin thuds]

45:27.895 --> 45:29.188
[Lin grunting in pain]

45:29.188 --> 45:30.022
[Percival kicking]

45:31.899 --> 45:32.900
[Lin groans]

45:33.442 --> 45:36.361
ELEANOR:
I never forgave Pa for what he'd done.

45:37.738 --> 45:39.448
But I was starting to understand

45:39.448 --> 45:44.828
how each of our choices,
not luck, leads us to the next,

45:45.746 --> 45:47.497
until, little by little,

45:48.624 --> 45:51.710
we wake up one day
wondering how we ever got here.

45:57.132 --> 45:58.884
[glass shattering]

45:59.551 --> 46:02.387
MAN: Coolies, go home!
Chiney not welcome!

46:02.387 --> 46:04.014
[speaking Hakka]

46:14.483 --> 46:18.695
[speaking Hakka]

46:22.407 --> 46:23.242
YOUNG LIN: Mm.

46:27.162 --> 46:29.164
[indistinct chatter]

46:33.669 --> 46:36.672
[people clamoring]

46:39.633 --> 46:41.635
[roosters clucking]

46:42.469 --> 46:44.471
[fence rattling]

46:44.763 --> 46:46.765
[indistinct shouting]

46:49.810 --> 46:51.812
[frenzied squawking and clucking]

46:55.440 --> 46:57.150
[excited chattering]

46:58.402 --> 46:59.653
[fence rattling]

47:03.866 --> 47:07.160
[Lin and Ba Ba speaking Hakka]

47:18.005 --> 47:20.007
[speaking Hakka]

47:27.472 --> 47:30.475
♪ poignant music playing ♪

47:42.154 --> 47:45.407
- That'll be...
one pound and four shillings.

47:51.705 --> 47:53.790
- How much for the rice and peas alone?

47:54.291 --> 47:57.211
My mother's sick, so she can't keep down.

47:58.253 --> 47:59.421
- Silly me.

47:59.421 --> 48:01.715
Everything half off today
to make room for new goods.

48:02.716 --> 48:03.842
- Don't pity me.

48:04.343 --> 48:06.970
- Pity a pretty thing like you?
No, no, no, no.

48:06.970 --> 48:08.764
It's just your lucky day today, is all.

48:11.141 --> 48:12.434
That'll be...

48:14.019 --> 48:15.437
[Lin quietly muttering]

48:15.521 --> 48:16.897
12 shillings.

48:20.359 --> 48:22.903
♪

48:30.244 --> 48:31.203
[Mathilda chuckles]

48:31.828 --> 48:33.080
- You have flour in your hair.

48:34.498 --> 48:36.458
Come, come.
- Hmm?

48:41.255 --> 48:44.466
- Wow. Me never feel hair like this.

48:45.509 --> 48:47.219
- And what kinda hair is that?

48:47.219 --> 48:48.637
- Black and straight.

48:49.721 --> 48:51.807
And coarse as a brush.

49:00.607 --> 49:01.608
Thank you.

49:08.782 --> 49:10.117
[speaking Hakka]

49:23.130 --> 49:26.133
♪ Will You Love Me Tomorrow
by The Shirelles playing ♪

49:30.512 --> 49:35.267
- ♪ Tonight, you're mine completely ♪

49:37.352 --> 49:41.690
♪ You give your love so sweetly... ♪

49:41.690 --> 49:43.400
ELEANOR:
For as long as I can remember,

49:43.984 --> 49:46.320
the story Pa told everyone was that

49:46.320 --> 49:49.656
he learned
how to weigh risk against reward,

49:50.282 --> 49:54.745
and his willingness to take a chance
put food on his parents' table

49:55.579 --> 49:56.538
and ours.

49:57.623 --> 50:02.836
- ♪ Is this a lasting treasure? ♪

50:02.836 --> 50:05.047
[spectators cheering]

50:05.047 --> 50:09.843
- ♪ Or just a moment's pleasure? ♪

50:11.136 --> 50:17.142
♪ Can I believe the magic of your sighs? ♪

50:18.852 --> 50:23.440
♪ Will you still love me tomorrow? ♪

50:24.441 --> 50:25.609
[squawking]

50:27.778 --> 50:29.780
[indistinct shouting and cheers]

50:36.828 --> 50:40.249
ELEANOR:
But the story Pa wasn't telling anyone

50:40.249 --> 50:43.001
was that there's no real formula to luck.

50:44.002 --> 50:46.755
He just thought his would never run out.

50:46.755 --> 50:51.635
- ♪ Will you still love me tomorrow? ♪

50:53.428 --> 50:58.141
♪ Will you still love me tomorrow? ♪

51:00.102 --> 51:05.065
♪ Will you still love me tomorrow? ♪

51:09.069 --> 51:10.070
- Where's my money?

51:10.946 --> 51:12.114
- I'll get it to you soon.

51:12.698 --> 51:14.783
The business will pick up again.
I'm sure of it.

51:18.912 --> 51:22.624
- I have a way
that you can... erase all your debts.

51:24.168 --> 51:25.169
Now.

51:28.672 --> 51:29.673
Without money.

51:30.257 --> 51:33.260
♪ ominous music playing ♪

51:35.220 --> 51:36.930
- She only 16!

51:36.930 --> 51:38.557
- No better age for a wife.

51:41.476 --> 51:43.812
- Eh-- Covey's got a mouth on her.

51:43.812 --> 51:45.606
Trust me, Clarence.
You don't want the trouble.

51:45.898 --> 51:47.024
[Little Man chuckling]

51:47.482 --> 51:50.194
- Nothing worse than a girl
who doesn't know when to shut her mouth.

51:55.949 --> 51:58.035
- You will get your money, with interest.

51:58.035 --> 51:59.036
- I better.

51:59.036 --> 52:00.871
And if you try to make a fool of me,

52:04.958 --> 52:06.919
well, I'll arrange the marriage myself.

52:08.712 --> 52:11.715
♪ ominous music continues playing ♪

52:18.430 --> 52:19.556
LITTLE MAN:
To my wife!

52:19.556 --> 52:21.558
[guests cheering]

52:27.231 --> 52:29.650
[Indistinct chatter]

52:32.861 --> 52:33.946
[camera shutter snaps]

52:38.200 --> 52:40.202
♪ lively music playing ♪

52:45.249 --> 52:48.544
- Here he is, the proud pa of the bride--

52:54.174 --> 52:56.385
MAN:
Excuse me, sir, can we help you? You good?

52:58.262 --> 52:59.388
[Lin exhales sharply]

53:00.430 --> 53:02.683
[heavy breaths]

53:11.775 --> 53:13.110
PEARL:
I thought that was you.

53:16.738 --> 53:18.115
- What have I done, Pearl?

53:18.115 --> 53:19.616
How did I let this happen?

53:19.616 --> 53:21.493
- Now you're asking this?

53:22.202 --> 53:24.246
- All I ever wanted to do
was help my family.

53:25.247 --> 53:26.999
Someone needs to do something.

53:26.999 --> 53:28.500
Maybe it's not too late.

53:28.500 --> 53:29.501
- Enough!

53:30.127 --> 53:32.171
Get back out there
before someone sees you.

53:35.299 --> 53:37.968
♪ upbeat calypso music playing ♪

53:37.968 --> 53:39.344
- Let go of me!

53:40.429 --> 53:41.722
We have to stop this!

53:42.556 --> 53:43.807
We have to find a way.

53:44.766 --> 53:46.894
- The last thing
that poor girl needs right now

53:46.894 --> 53:50.480
is for her father to make a scene
on top of everything else.

53:58.030 --> 53:59.031
What is it?

53:59.615 --> 54:01.116
- That Gibbs Grant boy.

54:01.825 --> 54:02.826
He was here.

54:04.578 --> 54:05.579
- You're drunk.

54:06.205 --> 54:08.457
That boy left for London weeks ago.

54:08.457 --> 54:09.583
[thud]

54:10.209 --> 54:11.293
[guests gasp and scream]

54:12.127 --> 54:13.128
- Clarence?

54:15.255 --> 54:16.340
Clarence!

54:17.591 --> 54:19.092
- Looks like someone found a way.

54:19.092 --> 54:20.844
PERCIVAL: Call an ambulance!
Call for somebody!

54:20.844 --> 54:22.137
Give me a tissue.

54:22.679 --> 54:24.139
Water. Water.

54:25.390 --> 54:28.143
My brother, he needs help.
Call an ambulance. My brother!

54:31.605 --> 54:34.149
ELEANOR:
When I think of my pa now,

54:34.149 --> 54:39.154
I imagine that hope
was really all he had left in the end.

54:40.948 --> 54:44.660
Hope that if he couldn't rescue me
from a marriage to Little Man,

54:45.369 --> 54:46.662
someone else would.

54:48.497 --> 54:50.707
And someone else did.

54:52.835 --> 54:56.672
For a while,
everyone thought it was Pa.

54:57.172 --> 54:59.967
Even Bunny sent me away thinking that,

55:00.801 --> 55:02.010
but she was wrong.

55:03.220 --> 55:05.597
Pa didn't come through.

55:06.807 --> 55:09.226
His luck had run out.

55:12.104 --> 55:15.065
[people screaming, coughing]

55:19.695 --> 55:20.696
- Elly!

55:21.280 --> 55:22.406
Elly!

55:23.365 --> 55:25.367
[grunting]

55:27.494 --> 55:28.704
[groaning]

55:45.012 --> 55:47.890
♪ solemn music playing ♪

56:09.369 --> 56:10.370
NURSE [echoing]:
Eleanor?

56:15.459 --> 56:16.793
Happy new year, Eleanor.

56:18.212 --> 56:19.213
- Coventina.

56:19.880 --> 56:21.215
- Coventina Brown?

56:22.508 --> 56:23.509
Was she your friend?

56:25.135 --> 56:26.303
I'm so sorry.

56:27.596 --> 56:28.805
She didn't make it.

56:29.932 --> 56:30.933
- Elly?

56:32.267 --> 56:33.101
No.

56:33.644 --> 56:34.478
God.

56:34.937 --> 56:36.855
Elly--
- Elly? Is that short for--

56:37.814 --> 56:39.816
Would you rather I called you Elly, dear?

56:39.816 --> 56:41.360
- No.
- Sorry?

56:43.070 --> 56:45.614
ELEANOR:
Pa's lucky streak may have ended.

56:46.573 --> 56:47.574
Not mine.

56:48.408 --> 56:50.661
I had been given a second chance.

56:51.411 --> 56:53.038
And a new story to tell.

56:54.581 --> 56:55.582
B and B,

56:56.291 --> 56:58.710
this is how I really became your ma,

57:00.295 --> 57:01.755
the woman you know as...

57:02.881 --> 57:03.882
- Eleanor.

57:06.802 --> 57:09.388
♪ poignant music playing ♪
